    <h1>Database MCP Server Tools</h1>
    <p>This repository provides SQL scripts to create user-defined tools for a Model Context Protocol (MCP) server. These tools facilitate common database introspection and interaction tasks.</p>

    <h2>Implementation Approach</h2>
    <p>For each tool, the implementation follows a two-step process:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Create Database Function:</strong> Defines the backend logic in the database.</li>
        <li><strong>Define MCP Tool:</strong> Wraps the function for use by the MCP server.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Pagination Parameters</h2>
    <div class="pagination-note">
        <strong>Note:</strong> Tools that return large datasets support pagination to optimize performance:
        <ul>
            <li><code>limit</code>: Sets the page size (max records to return).</li>
            <li><code>offset</code>: Indicates the number of records to skip before applying the limit.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Available Tools</h2>

    <h3>1. <code>LIST_SCHEMA</code></h3>
    <p>Returns the list of schemas available to the user in the database.</p>

    <h3>2. <code>LIST_OBJECTS</code></h3>
    <p>Returns the list of database objects (tables, views, etc.) for a specified schema.</p>
    <p><strong>Parameters:</strong> <code>schema_name</code>, <code>limit</code>, <code>offset</code></p>

    <h3>3. <code>GET_OBJECT_DETAILS</code></h3>
    <p>Returns detailed information about a specific database object (e.g., column names, types) within the given schema.</p>
    <p><strong>Parameters:</strong> <code>schema_name</code>, <code>object_name</code></p>

    <h3>4. <code>EXECUTE_SQL</code></h3>
    <p>Runs the provided SQL query statement directly.</p>
    <p><strong>Usage:</strong> Provide the SQL query string <strong>without</strong> a trailing semicolon.</p>

    <h2>SQL Setup Script</h2>
    <pre><code>
-- 1. LIST_SCHEMA
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION list_schemas()
RETURNS TABLE(schema_name TEXT) AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY 
    SELECT nspname::TEXT 
    FROM pg_namespace 
    WHERE nspname NOT LIKE 'pg_%' AND nspname != 'information_schema';
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 2. LIST_OBJECTS (with pagination)
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION list_objects(p_schema TEXT, p_limit INT, p_offset INT)
RETURNS TABLE(object_name TEXT, object_type TEXT) AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY 
    SELECT tablename::TEXT, 'table'::TEXT 
    FROM pg_tables WHERE schemaname = p_schema
    UNION ALL
    SELECT viewname::TEXT, 'view'::TEXT 
    FROM pg_views WHERE schemaname = p_schema
    LIMIT p_limit OFFSET p_offset;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 3. GET_OBJECT_DETAILS
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION get_object_details(p_schema TEXT, p_object TEXT)
RETURNS TABLE(column_name TEXT, data_type TEXT, is_nullable TEXT) AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY 
    SELECT column_name::TEXT, data_type::TEXT, is_nullable::TEXT
    FROM information_schema.columns
    WHERE table_schema = p_schema AND table_name = p_object;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- 4. EXECUTE_SQL
-- Note: Security considerations should be applied to dynamic SQL in production
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION execute_sql(p_query TEXT)
RETURNS SETOF RECORD AS $$
BEGIN
    RETURN QUERY EXECUTE p_query;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
    </code></pre>

